<h2>HVAC Systems in Texas</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>

<p>Texas's climate demands highly efficient cooling systems capable of handling extreme summer temperatures while maintaining reasonable heating capacity for occasional winter cold snaps. The state's diverse climate zones range from humid subtropical in the east to arid desert in the west, but all regions share the common characteristic of intense summer heat. Air conditioning systems must operate efficiently at outdoor temperatures exceeding 100¬∞F for extended periods, making high SEER (Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio) ratings essential for cost-effective operation.</p>

<p>The recommended minimum SEER rating for Texas installations is 15, though systems with SEER ratings of 16-20 provide optimal efficiency and long-term savings. Heat pumps work exceptionally well in most Texas regions due to mild winters, offering both heating and cooling in a single, efficient system. However, traditional split systems with gas furnaces remain popular in northern Texas where occasional freezing temperatures can reduce heat pump efficiency.</p>

<p>Humidity control represents another critical consideration, particularly in coastal and eastern regions where summer humidity levels regularly exceed 80%. Modern HVAC systems should include variable-speed technology and enhanced dehumidification capabilities to maintain indoor comfort while minimizing energy consumption. Proper system sizing is crucial in Texas, as oversized units cycle frequently and fail to adequately remove humidity, while undersized systems struggle to maintain comfortable temperatures during peak summer conditions.</p>

