<h2>Texas Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Texas offers several attractive incentives for solar and HVAC installations, making these energy-efficient investments more affordable and accelerating payback periods. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) remains the most significant incentive, allowing homeowners to deduct 30% of the total solar system cost from their federal taxes. This credit applies to the full installed cost, including equipment, labor, permits, and interconnection fees. For a typical \$20,000 solar installation, this translates to \$6,000 in tax savings. The 30% credit is available through 2032, then steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> The most valuable incentive available, this credit applies to the entire cost of solar installations, including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and professional installation. Homeowners can claim the credit over multiple tax years if their tax liability is insufficient to use the full credit in the installation year. The credit has no cap, making it equally valuable for small and large installations.</li>

<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Texas state law exempts the added value of solar installations from property tax assessments. This means while solar panels increase home value, they don't increase annual property tax bills. For a \$20,000 solar system that adds \$15,000 to home value, this exemption saves approximately \$300-500 annually depending on local tax rates.</li>

<li><strong>Oncor Energy Efficiency Programs:</strong> Oncor offers various rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, smart thermostats, and energy-efficient appliances. Heat pump rebates range from \$400-800 depending on efficiency ratings, while smart thermostat rebates provide \$50-85 per unit. These programs also include free energy audits and weatherization assistance.</li>

<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Many Texas municipalities and electric cooperatives offer additional incentives. Austin Energy provides solar rebates up to \$2,500 for residential installations, while San Antonio's CPS Energy offers performance-based incentives for solar production. These programs vary by location and may include cash rebates, performance payments, or reduced interconnection fees.</li>

<li><strong>Maximizing Incentives:</strong> To maximize benefits, homeowners should coordinate solar and HVAC installations to capture multiple rebates. Installing high-efficiency HVAC systems alongside solar panels creates a synergistic effect, reducing overall energy consumption while maximizing solar production value. Proper timing ensures eligibility for all available programs while optimizing tax benefits across multiple years.</li>
</ul>

